Now I have a complete picture of the codebase and all the specifications. Let me synthesize this into a detailed implementation plan.

---

# Implementation Plan: Adding 5 Psychological Assessments to Couples App

## Current State Summary

The app currently has a single assessment (ECR-R) hardcoded throughout:
- **Types** (`/Users/shaharrabi/couples-app-v0.1/types/index.ts`): Only ECR-R types; `AssessmentType = 'ecr-r'`
- **Questions** (`/Users/shaharrabi/couples-app-v0.1/utils/questions.ts`): 36 ECR-R questions, 7-point Likert labels
- **Scoring** (`/Users/shaharrabi/couples-app-v0.1/utils/scoring.ts`): `calculateECRRScores()` only
- **Interpretations** (`/Users/shaharrabi/couples-app-v0.1/utils/interpretations.ts`): Attachment style interpretations only
- **Assessment Screen** (`/Users/shaharrabi/couples-app-v0.1/app/(app)/assessment.tsx`): Hardcoded to ECR-R -- imports `ECR_R_QUESTIONS`, `LIKERT_LABELS`, `calculateECRRScores`, uses `TOTAL_QUESTIONS=36`, saves to `ecr_r_assessments` table, passes anxiety/avoidance/attachment params to results
- **Home Screen** (`/Users/shaharrabi/couples-app-v0.1/app/(app)/home.tsx`): Hardcoded to `ecr_r_progress` AsyncStorage key, shows single assessment
- **Results Screen** (`/Users/shaharrabi/couples-app-v0.1/app/(app)/results.tsx`): Hardcoded to display `anxietyScore`/`avoidanceScore`/`attachmentStyle`
- **Layout** (`/Users/shaharrabi/couples-app-v0.1/app/(app)/_layout.tsx`): Three screens only: `home`, `assessment`, `results`
- **Database**: Currently using a dedicated `ecr_r_assessments` table per the user decision to switch to a single unified `assessments` table with `type` field + JSONB

The existing code uses Expo Router file-based routing, Supabase auth, AsyncStorage for in-progress persistence, and a clean theme constants file at `/Users/shaharrabi/couples-app-v0.1/constants/theme.ts`.

The spec at `/Users/shaharrabi/couples-app-v0.1/archived-specs/assessment-instruments-specification-complete.md` contains all 6 instruments with full item lists and scoring algorithms. The database spec at `/Users/shaharrabi/couples-app-v0.1/archived-specs/database-schema-specification.md` describes a more elaborate schema that this v0.1 simplifies.

---

## Architecture Decision: The AssessmentConfig Pattern

The core design problem is that each assessment differs along these axes:
1. **Question types**: Likert (varying scales: 5, 6, 7, 10-point), text input, multiple choice, ranking
2. **Scale labels**: Different labels per assessment (e.g., "Strongly Disagree..Strongly Agree" vs "Never..Always" vs "Not at all true..Very true")
3. **Scoring logic**: Different reverse-scored items, different subscale compositions, different output shapes
4. **Interpretation**: Different output visualizations per assessment
5. **Length**: 20 to 120 items, with the 120-item one needing section breaks

The solution: an `AssessmentConfig` object that fully describes each assessment, a generic assessment engine screen that reads the config, and per-assessment scoring functions and results components.

---

## Phase A: Generalize Infrastructure (Foundation)

### A1. Expand the type system

**File: `/Users/shaharrabi/couples-app-v0.1/types/index.ts`** -- Modify

Replace the current content with a comprehensive type system. Key types to define:

```typescript
// Assessment type enum -- all 6 assessments
export type AssessmentType = 
  | 'ecr-r' 
  | 'ipip-neo-120' 
  | 'values' 
  | 'sseit' 
  | 'dutch' 
  | 'dsi-r';

// Question input types that the generic screen must support
export type QuestionInputType = 'likert' | 'text' | 'choice' | 'ranking';

// A single Likert label option
export interface LikertOption {
  value: number;
  label: string;
}

// A single choice option (for Values scenarios)
export interface ChoiceOption {
  key: string;       // 'A', 'B', 'C', 'D'
  text: string;
  coding: string;    // e.g., 'honesty_high', 'avoidance'
}

// Generic question definition
export interface GenericQuestion {
  id: number;            // 1-indexed
  text: string;
  inputType: QuestionInputType;
  subscale?: string;     // Which subscale this belongs to
  reverseScored?: boolean;
  // For text questions:
  charLimit?: number;
  placeholder?: string;
  // For choice questions:
  choices?: ChoiceOption[];
  // For ranking questions:
  rankingItems?: { id: string; label: string }[];
  rankCount?: number;    // How many to select (e.g., 5 for Values top-5)
}

// Section definition for long assessments
export interface AssessmentSection {
  id: string;
  title: string;
  description?: string;
  questionRange: [number, number];  // [startIndex, endIndex] inclusive, 0-based
}

// The master config for an assessment
export interface AssessmentConfig {
  type: AssessmentType;
  name: string;          // Display name
  shortName: string;     // For cards/badges
  description: string;   // One-line description
  instructions: string;  // Pre-assessment instructions text
  estimatedMinutes: number;
  totalQuestions: number;
  questions: GenericQuestion[];
  likertScale?: LikertOption[];  // Default Likert scale for this assessment
  sections?: AssessmentSection[];  // For section breaks
  scoringFn: (responses: Record<string, any>) => any;  // Returns typed scores
  progressKey: string;   // AsyncStorage key for in-progress state
}

// Unified Supabase table row shape
export interface AssessmentRecord {
  id: string;
  user_id: string;
  type: AssessmentType;
  responses: Record<string, any>;  // JSONB -- raw responses
  scores: Record<string, any>;     // JSONB -- computed scores
  completed_at: string;
  created_at: string;
}

// Per-assessment score types (keep ECRRScores, add others)
export interface ECRRScores { /* existing */ }
export interface DUTCHScores {
  subscaleScores: Record<string, { sum: number; mean: number }>;
  primaryStyle: string;
  secondaryStyle: string;
}
export interface SSEITScores {
  totalScore: number;
  totalMean: number;
  totalNormalized: number;
  subscaleScores: Record<string, { sum: number; mean: number; itemCount: number }>;
  subscaleNormalized: Record<string, number>;
}
export interface DSIRScores {
  totalMean: number;
  totalNormalized: number;
  subscaleScores: Record<string, { sum: number; mean: number; itemCount: number }>;
  subscaleNormalized: Record<string, number>;
}
export interface IPIPScores {
  domainScores: Record<string, { sum: number; mean: number }>;
  domainPercentiles: Record<string, number>;
  facetScores: Record<string, { sum: number; mean: number }>;
  facetPercentiles: Record<string, number>;
}
export interface ValuesScores {
  domainScores: Record<string, { importance: number; accordance: number; gap: number }>;
  top5Values: string[];
  qualitativeResponses: { partnerIdentity: string; nonNegotiables: string; aspirationalVision: string };
  actionResponses: Record<string, string>;
  avoidanceTendency: number;
  balancedTendency: number;
  highGapDomains: string[];
}
```

**Rationale**: The `AssessmentConfig` is the central abstraction. Each assessment provides one. The generic screens consume configs. The `scoringFn` lives on the config so the assessment screen does not need to import specific scoring functions.

### A2. Create the assessment registry

**File: `/Users/shaharrabi/couples-app-v0.1/utils/assessments/registry.ts`** -- New file

This is the single import point. It maps `AssessmentType` to `AssessmentConfig`:

```typescript
import { AssessmentType, AssessmentConfig } from '@/types';
import { ecrRConfig } from './configs/ecr-r';
// Future: import other configs

const ASSESSMENT_REGISTRY: Record<AssessmentType, AssessmentConfig> = {
  'ecr-r': ecrRConfig,
  // More added in later phases
};

export function getAssessmentConfig(type: AssessmentType): AssessmentConfig {
  return ASSESSMENT_REGISTRY[type];
}

export function getAllAssessments(): AssessmentConfig[] {
  return Object.values(ASSESSMENT_REGISTRY);
}

// Order for display on home screen
export const ASSESSMENT_ORDER: AssessmentType[] = [
  'ecr-r', 'dutch', 'sseit', 'dsi-r', 'ipip-neo-120', 'values'
];
```

### A3. Refactor ECR-R into the config pattern

**File: `/Users/shaharrabi/couples-app-v0.1/utils/assessments/configs/ecr-r.ts`** -- New file

Move the existing questions, scoring, and interpretations into a single config object. The existing `utils/questions.ts`, `utils/scoring.ts`, and `utils/interpretations.ts` will remain as-is initially (no need to delete -- they just become dead code once the refactor is done). The new file imports nothing from the old ones; it is self-contained.

The config file contains:
- `ECR_R_QUESTIONS` array converted to `GenericQuestion[]` format (adding `inputType: 'likert'`)
- `ECR_R_LIKERT_SCALE` (7-point, same labels as current `LIKERT_LABELS`)
- `calculateECRRScores` function (same logic as current `utils/scoring.ts`)
- `ecrRConfig: AssessmentConfig` tying it all together

### A4. Create the unified Supabase table

**Database migration** (run manually or via Supabase dashboard):

```sql
CREATE TABLE assessments (
  id UUID PRIMARY KEY DEFAULT gen_random_uuid(),
  user_id UUID NOT NULL REFERENCES auth.users(id) ON DELETE CASCADE,
  type TEXT NOT NULL,       -- 'ecr-r', 'dutch', 'sseit', etc.
  responses JSONB NOT NULL, -- Raw responses array/object
  scores JSONB NOT NULL,    -- Computed scores
  completed_at TIMESTAMPTZ NOT NULL DEFAULT NOW(),
  created_at TIMESTAMPTZ NOT NULL DEFAULT NOW()
);

-- Index for user's assessments by type
CREATE INDEX idx_assessments_user_type ON assessments(user_id, type, completed_at DESC);

-- RLS policy
ALTER TABLE assessments ENABLE ROW LEVEL SECURITY;
CREATE POLICY "Users can manage own assessments" ON assessments
  FOR ALL USING (auth.uid() = user_id);
```

Optionally migrate existing data from `ecr_r_assessments` to the new table. The old table can remain for backward compatibility.

### A5. Refactor the assessment screen to be generic

**File: `/Users/shaharrabi/couples-app-v0.1/app/(app)/assessment.tsx`** -- Modify (major rewrite)

The screen receives the assessment type via route params: `router.push({ pathname: '/(app)/assessment', params: { type: 'dutch' } })`.

Key changes:
- Read `type` from `useLocalSearchParams`
- Call `getAssessmentConfig(type)` to get the config
- Use `config.questions` instead of `ECR_R_QUESTIONS`
- Use `config.likertScale` instead of `LIKERT_LABELS`
- Use `config.totalQuestions` instead of hardcoded `36`
- Use `config.progressKey` for AsyncStorage
- The response state becomes `Record<string, any>` to support different input types (number for Likert, string for text, etc.)
- Render different input components based on `question.inputType`:
  - `'likert'` -> existing radio button UI (parameterized by scale)
  - `'text'` -> `TextInput` with `charLimit`
  - `'choice'` -> option cards (like Likert but with text options)
  - `'ranking'` -> drag-to-rank UI (Phase E, for Values)
- Section breaks: when entering a new section (from `config.sections`), show a section break screen with title/description and a "Continue" button
- On submit: call `config.scoringFn(responses)`, save to `assessments` table with `type` field
- Navigate to results with `type` param

The progress bar should show section-aware progress for sectioned assessments (e.g., "Section 2 of 5 -- Question 3 of 24").

### A6. Refactor the home screen to show all assessments

**File: `/Users/shaharrabi/couples-app-v0.1/app/(app)/home.tsx`** -- Modify (major rewrite)

Replace the single-assessment view with an assessment hub:

- Import `getAllAssessments()` and `ASSESSMENT_ORDER`
- On mount, query Supabase for `assessments` where `user_id = user.id` to get completion status per type
- Also check AsyncStorage for each assessment's `progressKey` to detect in-progress state
- Render a `FlatList` or `ScrollView` of assessment cards, each showing:
  - Name, short description, estimated time
  - Status badge: "Not Started", "In Progress (Q 14/20)", "Completed"
  - A button: "Start", "Continue", or "Retake"
- Tapping a card navigates to `/(app)/assessment?type=ecr-r`

### A7. Create per-assessment results routing

**File: `/Users/shaharrabi/couples-app-v0.1/app/(app)/results.tsx`** -- Modify

Two approaches:
1. **Single results screen with conditional rendering** -- simpler routing, more complex component
2. **Per-assessment results screens** -- cleaner separation, more files

Recommended: **Hybrid approach**. Keep `results.tsx` as a router that reads the `type` param and delegates to a per-assessment results component:

```tsx
// app/(app)/results.tsx
import { useLocalSearchParams } from 'expo-router';
import ECRRResults from '@/components/results/ECRRResults';
import DUTCHResults from '@/components/results/DUTCHResults';
// ... etc.

export default function ResultsScreen() {
  const { type, scores } = useLocalSearchParams<{ type: string; scores: string }>();
  const parsedScores = JSON.parse(scores);

  switch (type) {
    case 'ecr-r': return <ECRRResults scores={parsedScores} />;
    case 'dutch': return <DUTCHResults scores={parsedScores} />;
    // ... etc.
    default: return <Text>Unknown assessment type</Text>;
  }
}
```

The results components live under `/Users/shaharrabi/couples-app-v0.1/components/results/`.

### A8. Update the app layout

**File: `/Users/shaharrabi/couples-app-v0.1/app/(app)/_layout.tsx`** -- Minor modification

No new routes needed -- the existing `home`, `assessment`, and `results` routes work. The assessment type is passed via search params rather than being baked into the route path. This avoids proliferating route files.

---

## Phase B: DUTCH (Simplest Assessment -- Proof of Concept)

Build DUTCH first to validate the generic infrastructure works end-to-end.

### B1. Create DUTCH config

**File: `/Users/shaharrabi/couples-app-v0.1/utils/assessments/configs/dutch.ts`** -- New file

Contains:
- 20 questions as `GenericQuestion[]` with `inputType: 'likert'`, no reverse scoring
- 5-point Likert scale: "Never", "Rarely", "Sometimes", "Often", "Always"
- Subscale assignments: Yielding (items 1,6,11,16), Compromising (2,7,12,17), Forcing (3,8,13,18), Problem-Solving (4,9,14,19), Avoiding (5,10,15,20) -- using 0-indexed arrays
- `scoreDUTCH()` function: compute subscale sums/means, determine primary/secondary style
- Export `dutchConfig: AssessmentConfig`

All item text comes directly from the spec at line 1147-1168 of the assessment instruments specification.

### B2. Create DUTCH results component

**File: `/Users/shaharrabi/couples-app-v0.1/components/results/DUTCHResults.tsx`** -- New file

Display:
- 5 horizontal bar charts showing subscale means (1-5 scale)
- Primary style highlighted with interpretation text
- Secondary style shown
- Style descriptions from the spec (Yielding, Compromising, Forcing, Problem-Solving, Avoiding)
- Growth tip for the primary style

### B3. Create DUTCH interpretations

**File: `/Users/shaharrabi/couples-app-v0.1/utils/assessments/interpretations/dutch.ts`** -- New file

Contains interpretation text for each of the 5 conflict styles, similar in tone to the existing ECR-R interpretations (warm, non-judgmental, growth-oriented).

### B4. Register DUTCH and test

Add `'dutch': dutchConfig` to the registry. The home screen should now show 2 assessments. Navigating to DUTCH should show 20 questions with 5-point scale, compute scores, and display results.

---

## Phase C: SSEIT (33 items, straightforward Likert)

### C1. Create SSEIT config

**File: `/Users/shaharrabi/couples-app-v0.1/utils/assessments/configs/sseit.ts`** -- New file

- 33 questions, 5-point Likert ("Strongly Disagree" to "Strongly Agree")
- 3 reverse-scored items: 5, 28, 33 (1-indexed)
- 4 subscales: Perception (14 items), Managing Own (4), Managing Others (5), Utilization (10)
- Scoring: reverse items via `6 - score`, compute subscale sums/means, normalize to 0-100

### C2. Create SSEIT results component

