## Key Design Details

### How the generic assessment screen handles different input types

In `assessment.tsx`, the question rendering area becomes a switch:

```tsx
const question = config.questions[currentIndex];

// In the render:
{question.inputType === 'likert' && (
  <LikertInput 
    scale={config.likertScale!} 
    value={responses[currentIndex]} 
    onSelect={(val) => handleSelect(currentIndex, val)} 
  />
)}
{question.inputType === 'text' && (
  <TextResponseInput
    value={responses[currentIndex] || ''}
    charLimit={question.charLimit || 500}
    placeholder={question.placeholder}
    onChange={(text) => handleSelect(currentIndex, text)}
  />
)}
{question.inputType === 'choice' && (
  <ChoiceInput
    choices={question.choices!}
    value={responses[currentIndex]}
    onSelect={(key) => handleSelect(currentIndex, key)}
  />
)}
{question.inputType === 'ranking' && (
  <RankingInput
    items={question.rankingItems!}
    count={question.rankCount!}
    value={responses[currentIndex] || []}
    onChange={(ranked) => handleSelect(currentIndex, ranked)}
  />
)}
```

The `responses` state changes from `(number | null)[]` to `(any | null)[]` to accommodate different response types. The `handleSelect` and validation logic become type-aware.

### How section breaks work

In `handleNext`, before advancing:
```typescript
const nextIndex = currentIndex + 1;
if (config.sections) {
  const currentSection = config.sections.find(s => 
    currentIndex >= s.questionRange[0] && currentIndex <= s.questionRange[1]
  );
  const nextSection = config.sections.find(s =>
    nextIndex >= s.questionRange[0] && nextIndex <= s.questionRange[1]
  );
  if (currentSection && nextSection && currentSection.id !== nextSection.id) {
    setShowSectionBreak(nextSection);
    return; // Don't advance yet
  }
}
setCurrentIndex(nextIndex);
```

The section break overlay shows a card with the section title/description and "Continue" / "Save & Exit" buttons.

### How AsyncStorage progress persistence works for generic assessments

Each assessment uses `config.progressKey` as its AsyncStorage key. The stored shape is:
```json
{
  "responses": [1, 3, null, 5, ...],
  "currentIndex": 14
}
```
Same pattern as current ECR-R, but per-assessment keys like `dutch_progress`, `sseit_progress`, etc.

### How the home screen checks completion status

```typescript
// On mount:
const { data: completed } = await supabase
  .from('assessments')
  .select('type, completed_at')
  .eq('user_id', user.id)
  .order('completed_at', { ascending: false });

// Build completion map:
const completionMap: Record<AssessmentType, { completedAt: string } | null> = {};
for (const row of completed) {
  if (!completionMap[row.type]) completionMap[row.type] = { completedAt: row.completed_at };
}

// Check in-progress from AsyncStorage for each assessment:
for (const config of getAllAssessments()) {
  const saved = await AsyncStorage.getItem(config.progressKey);
  if (saved) { /* mark as in-progress with question count */ }
}
```

### How results are passed and displayed

On assessment completion:
```typescript
const scores = config.scoringFn(validResponses);
router.replace({
  pathname: '/(app)/results',
  params: {
    type: config.type,
    scores: JSON.stringify(scores),
  },
});
```

The results screen parses `scores` and renders the appropriate results component.

