- The response state becomes `Record<string, any>` to support different input types (number for Likert, string for text, etc.)
- Render different input components based on `question.inputType`:
  - `'likert'` -> existing radio button UI (parameterized by scale)
  - `'text'` -> `TextInput` with `charLimit`
  - `'choice'` -> option cards (like Likert but with text options)
  - `'ranking'` -> drag-to-rank UI (Phase E, for Values)
- Section breaks: when entering a new section (from `config.sections`), show a section break screen with title/description and a "Continue" button
- On submit: call `config.scoringFn(responses)`, save to `assessments` table with `type` field
- Navigate to results with `type` param

The progress bar should show section-aware progress for sectioned assessments (e.g., "Section 2 of 5 -- Question 3 of 24").

### A6. Refactor the home screen to show all assessments

**File: `/Users/shaharrabi/couples-app-v0.1/app/(app)/home.tsx`** -- Modify (major rewrite)

Replace the single-assessment view with an assessment hub:

- Import `getAllAssessments()` and `ASSESSMENT_ORDER`
- On mount, query Supabase for `assessments` where `user_id = user.id` to get completion status per type
- Also check AsyncStorage for each assessment's `progressKey` to detect in-progress state
- Render a `FlatList` or `ScrollView` of assessment cards, each showing:
  - Name, short description, estimated time
  - Status badge: "Not Started", "In Progress (Q 14/20)", "Completed"
  - A button: "Start", "Continue", or "Retake"
- Tapping a card navigates to `/(app)/assessment?type=ecr-r`

### A7. Create per-assessment results routing

**File: `/Users/shaharrabi/couples-app-v0.1/app/(app)/results.tsx`** -- Modify

Two approaches:
1. **Single results screen with conditional rendering** -- simpler routing, more complex component
2. **Per-assessment results screens** -- cleaner separation, more files

Recommended: **Hybrid approach**. Keep `results.tsx` as a router that reads the `type` param and delegates to a per-assessment results component:

```tsx
// app/(app)/results.tsx
import { useLocalSearchParams } from 'expo-router';
import ECRRResults from '@/components/results/ECRRResults';
import DUTCHResults from '@/components/results/DUTCHResults';
// ... etc.

export default function ResultsScreen() {
  const { type, scores } = useLocalSearchParams<{ type: string; scores: string }>();
  const parsedScores = JSON.parse(scores);

  switch (type) {
    case 'ecr-r': return <ECRRResults scores={parsedScores} />;
    case 'dutch': return <DUTCHResults scores={parsedScores} />;
    // ... etc.
    default: return <Text>Unknown assessment type</Text>;
  }
}
```

The results components live under `/Users/shaharrabi/couples-app-v0.1/components/results/`.

### A8. Update the app layout

**File: `/Users/shaharrabi/couples-app-v0.1/app/(app)/_layout.tsx`** -- Minor modification

No new routes needed -- the existing `home`, `assessment`, and `results` routes work. The assessment type is passed via search params rather than being baked into the route path. This avoids proliferating route files.

---

## Phase B: DUTCH (Simplest Assessment -- Proof of Concept)

Build DUTCH first to validate the generic infrastructure works end-to-end.

### B1. Create DUTCH config

**File: `/Users/shaharrabi/couples-app-v0.1/utils/assessments/configs/dutch.ts`** -- New file

Contains:
- 20 questions as `GenericQuestion[]` with `inputType: 'likert'`, no reverse scoring
- 5-point Likert scale: "Never", "Rarely", "Sometimes", "Often", "Always"
- Subscale assignments: Yielding (items 1,6,11,16), Compromising (2,7,12,17), Forcing (3,8,13,18), Problem-Solving (4,9,14,19), Avoiding (5,10,15,20) -- using 0-indexed arrays
- `scoreDUTCH()` function: compute subscale sums/means, determine primary/secondary style
- Export `dutchConfig: AssessmentConfig`

All item text comes directly from the spec at line 1147-1168 of the assessment instruments specification.

### B2. Create DUTCH results component

**File: `/Users/shaharrabi/couples-app-v0.1/components/results/DUTCHResults.tsx`** -- New file

Display:
- 5 horizontal bar charts showing subscale means (1-5 scale)
- Primary style highlighted with interpretation text
- Secondary style shown
- Style descriptions from the spec (Yielding, Compromising, Forcing, Problem-Solving, Avoiding)
- Growth tip for the primary style

### B3. Create DUTCH interpretations

**File: `/Users/shaharrabi/couples-app-v0.1/utils/assessments/interpretations/dutch.ts`** -- New file

Contains interpretation text for each of the 5 conflict styles, similar in tone to the existing ECR-R interpretations (warm, non-judgmental, growth-oriented).

### B4. Register DUTCH and test

Add `'dutch': dutchConfig` to the registry. The home screen should now show 2 assessments. Navigating to DUTCH should show 20 questions with 5-point scale, compute scores, and display results.

---

## Phase C: SSEIT (33 items, straightforward Likert)

### C1. Create SSEIT config

**File: `/Users/shaharrabi/couples-app-v0.1/utils/assessments/configs/sseit.ts`** -- New file

- 33 questions, 5-point Likert ("Strongly Disagree" to "Strongly Agree")
- 3 reverse-scored items: 5, 28, 33 (1-indexed)
- 4 subscales: Perception (14 items), Managing Own (4), Managing Others (5), Utilization (10)
- Scoring: reverse items via `6 - score`, compute subscale sums/means, normalize to 0-100

### C2. Create SSEIT results component

**File: `/Users/shaharrabi/couples-app-v0.1/components/results/SSEITResults.tsx`** -- New file

Display:
- Total EI score (normalized 0-100) as a prominent number with level label
- 4 subscale bars (normalized 0-100)
- Interpretation thresholds (Low/Below Average/Average/Above Average/High)

### C3. Register and add interpretations

**File: `/Users/shaharrabi/couples-app-v0.1/utils/assessments/interpretations/sseit.ts`** -- New file

---

## Phase D: DSI-R (46 items, 6-point Likert, double-reversal scoring)

### D1. Create DSI-R config

**File: `/Users/shaharrabi/couples-app-v0.1/utils/assessments/configs/dsi-r.ts`** -- New file

- 46 questions, 6-point Likert ("Not at all true of me" to "Very true of me")
- 12 reverse-scored items: 4, 5, 12, 15, 18, 26, 27, 32, 40, 42, 43, 45 (1-indexed)
- 4 subscales: Emotional Reactivity (11), I-Position (11), Emotional Cutoff (12), Fusion with Others (12)
- **Special scoring**: After reverse-scoring items, compute subscale raw mean, then reverse the mean with `7 - rawMean` so high = differentiated. Normalize to 0-100 with `((mean - 1) / 5) * 100`.

### D2. Create DSI-R results component

**File: `/Users/shaharrabi/couples-app-v0.1/components/results/DSIRResults.tsx`** -- New file

Display:
- Total differentiation score (0-100) with level
- 4 subscale bars (0-100)
- Subscale descriptions explaining what each measures
- Interpretation by level

---

## Phase E: IPIP-NEO-120 (120 items, section breaks)

This is the largest assessment and tests the section-break mechanism.

### E1. Create IPIP-NEO-120 config

**File: `/Users/shaharrabi/couples-app-v0.1/utils/assessments/configs/ipip-neo-120.ts`** -- New file

This will be a large file due to 120 items. Key structure:
- 120 questions, 5-point Likert ("Very Inaccurate" to "Very Accurate")
- 50+ reverse-scored items (all items marked with `-` key in the spec)
- 5 domains (Neuroticism, Extraversion, Openness, Agreeableness, Conscientiousness), each 24 items
- 30 facets, each 4 items
- 5 sections, one per domain, with section breaks every 24 items:
  ```typescript
  sections: [
    { id: 'neuroticism', title: 'Section 1 of 5', description: 'Questions about your emotional experiences', questionRange: [0, 23] },
    { id: 'extraversion', title: 'Section 2 of 5', description: 'Questions about social interaction', questionRange: [24, 47] },
    { id: 'openness', title: 'Section 3 of 5', description: 'Questions about your interests and values', questionRange: [48, 71] },
    { id: 'agreeableness', title: 'Section 4 of 5', description: 'Questions about how you relate to others', questionRange: [72, 95] },
    { id: 'conscientiousness', title: 'Section 5 of 5', description: 'Questions about organization and discipline', questionRange: [96, 119] },
  ]
  ```
- Scoring: reverse items via `6 - score`, compute facet sums/means, domain sums/means, approximate percentiles via logistic CDF

### E2. Implement section break UI in the generic assessment screen

In the assessment screen, add logic: when `currentIndex` crosses a section boundary AND the config has sections, show an interstitial view:
- Section title (e.g., "Section 3 of 5: Openness to Experience")
- Brief description
- Progress so far ("48 of 120 questions completed")
- "Take a Break" button (saves progress and goes home) + "Continue" button

This is triggered by checking `config.sections` boundaries during `handleNext`.

### E3. Create IPIP-NEO-120 results component

**File: `/Users/shaharrabi/couples-app-v0.1/components/results/IPIPResults.tsx`** -- New file

Display:
- Big Five radar/bar chart showing 5 domain percentiles
- Expandable domain sections showing 6 facet scores each
- Percentile-based level labels (Very Low through Very High)
- Domain-level descriptions

### E4. Register and add interpretations

**File: `/Users/shaharrabi/couples-app-v0.1/utils/assessments/interpretations/ipip-neo-120.ts`** -- New file

Domain and facet level interpretation text.

---

## Phase F: Custom Values Instrument (Most Complex -- 3 response types)

This assessment requires the most UI work because it has three distinct parts with different input types.

### F1. Create Values config

**File: `/Users/shaharrabi/couples-app-v0.1/utils/assessments/configs/values.ts`** -- New file

This config uses multiple question types:
- Part 1 (items 1-20): 20 Likert items on a 10-point scale, paired importance/accordance
- Part 1 ranking: A special ranking question (1 item, `inputType: 'ranking'`)
- Part 2 (items 21-23): 3 text input items (`inputType: 'text'`, with `charLimit`)
- Part 3 (items 24-31): 8 choice items (`inputType: 'choice'`, each with 4 `ChoiceOption`s)

The questions array will have 32 entries total (20 scaled + 1 ranking + 3 text + 8 choice).

Sections:
```typescript
sections: [
  { id: 'domain-assessment', title: 'Part 1: Your Values', description: 'Rate the importance of each value domain and how well you are living it', questionRange: [0, 20] },
  { id: 'relationship-clarification', title: 'Part 2: Your Vision', description: 'Share your thoughts about your ideal partnership', questionRange: [21, 23] },
  { id: 'values-in-action', title: 'Part 3: Real Situations', description: 'How you tend to respond in common relationship situations', questionRange: [24, 31] },
]
```

### F2. Implement ranking UI component

**File: `/Users/shaharrabi/couples-app-v0.1/components/assessment/RankingInput.tsx`** -- New file

A drag-to-reorder component for selecting and ranking top 5 values from 10 domains. Can use `react-native-gesture-handler` (already in dependencies) for drag. Alternatively, a simpler tap-to-select approach where the user taps items in order of priority (1st, 2nd, 3rd, 4th, 5th) -- this is more mobile-friendly and avoids complex drag gesture code.

### F3. Implement text input component

**File: `/Users/shaharrabi/couples-app-v0.1/components/assessment/TextInput.tsx`** -- New file (or inline)

A `TextInput` wrapper showing character count and limit. The generic assessment screen checks `question.inputType === 'text'` and renders this.

### F4. Implement choice input component

**File: `/Users/shaharrabi/couples-app-v0.1/components/assessment/ChoiceInput.tsx`** -- New file (or inline)

Renders 4 option cards (A, B, C, D) with text. Similar UI to the Likert radio buttons but with longer text and letter labels.

### F5. Create Values results component

**File: `/Users/shaharrabi/couples-app-v0.1/components/results/ValuesResults.tsx`** -- New file

Most complex results display:
- 10 value domain bars showing importance vs. accordance with gap highlighting
- Top 5 ranked values displayed as an ordered list
- High-gap domains called out
- Scenario response patterns (avoidance tendency, balanced tendency)
- Qualitative responses shown as read-only text cards

### F6. Create Values scoring and interpretations

Scoring function for Values lives in the config file. Interpretations in `/Users/shaharrabi/couples-app-v0.1/utils/assessments/interpretations/values.ts`.

